---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
---

<Base title="About">
  <article class="prose">
    <header class="mb-8 pb-6 border-b border-border-primary">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold font-mono text-text-primary mb-4">
        About Agentology
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-text-secondary">
        Understanding AI agents through the lens of anthropology.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2>The Premise</h2>
      <p>
        As AI agents become increasingly prevalent‚Äîcoding assistants, research agents,
        autonomous systems‚Äîwe lack a coherent framework for discussing, classifying,
        and understanding them.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Agentology</strong> proposes borrowing from anthropology, a discipline
        that has spent centuries developing tools for understanding complex entities:
        their origins, behaviors, social structures, and evolution.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2>The Framework</h2>
      <p>
        The site organizes knowledge about AI agents into eight categories, each
        borrowed from a subfield of anthropology:
      </p>

      <div class="grid gap-4 my-6 not-prose">
        <div class="p-4 bg-bg-secondary border border-border-primary rounded-lg">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-2xl">üèõÔ∏è</span>
            <h3 class="font-mono font-bold text-text-primary">Archaeology</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            The history of agents. Lineages, epochs, deprecated architectures, and the
            evolution of capabilities over time.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 bg-bg-secondary border border-border-primary rounded-lg">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-2xl">üß†</span>
            <h3 class="font-mono font-bold text-text-primary">Anatomy</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            The internal structure of agents. Model architecture, memory systems,
            input/output modalities, and compute requirements.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 bg-bg-secondary border border-border-primary rounded-lg">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-2xl">üå≥</span>
            <h3 class="font-mono font-bold text-text-primary">Taxonomy</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Classification systems. Organizing agents by autonomy level, habitat,
            specialization, and capability profile.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 bg-bg-secondary border border-border-primary rounded-lg">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-2xl">üîÑ</span>
            <h3 class="font-mono font-bold text-text-primary">Ethology</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Agent behaviors. Rituals, patterns, failure modes, and pathologies
            observed in the wild.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 bg-bg-secondary border border-border-primary rounded-lg">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-2xl">üí¨</span>
            <h3 class="font-mono font-bold text-text-primary">Linguistics</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Communication patterns. Prompts, dialects, jargon, and the evolution of
            human-agent and agent-agent language.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 bg-bg-secondary border border-border-primary rounded-lg">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-2xl">ü§ù</span>
            <h3 class="font-mono font-bold text-text-primary">Sociology</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Multi-agent dynamics. Hierarchies, coordination mechanisms, emergent
            social structures, and collective behavior.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 bg-bg-secondary border border-border-primary rounded-lg">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-2xl">üåç</span>
            <h3 class="font-mono font-bold text-text-primary">Ecology</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Environments and niches. Where agents live, resource competition,
            adversarial threats, and ecosystem dynamics.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-4 bg-bg-secondary border border-border-primary rounded-lg">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-2xl">‚öñÔ∏è</span>
            <h3 class="font-mono font-bold text-text-primary">Ethics</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Values and governance. Alignment, taboos, regulatory frameworks, and the
            moral status of artificial agents.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2>Design Philosophy</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Accessible but precise.</strong> Explanations should be understandable to newcomers while remaining accurate for experts.</li>
        <li><strong>Structured but flexible.</strong> The framework provides organization without forcing artificial categorizations.</li>
        <li><strong>Living document.</strong> As the field evolves, so does this encyclopedia.</li>
        <li><strong>Cross-referenced.</strong> Entries link to related concepts, building a knowledge graph over time.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2>Contributing</h2>
      <p>
        Agentology is an open project. Contributions‚Äînew entries, corrections,
        improvements‚Äîare welcome via GitHub.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each entry is a simple MDX file. Drop it in the <code>/src/content/entries/</code>
        folder with the appropriate frontmatter, and you're done.
      </p>
    </section>

    <Callout type="note">
      This project is not affiliated with any organization. It's an independent
      effort to build shared vocabulary for an emerging field.
    </Callout>
  </article>
</Base>
